## Problems Identified

### 1. Memory/FD Leak (Critical)
```rust
self.active_connections.push(socket.into_std().unwrap());
```
Connections are added to `Vec` but **never removed** when they close. This causes:
- Growing memory usage
- Potential FD leak if `TcpStream` isn't dropped

### 2. Unwrap on Accept (Causes Panic)
```rust
let (socket, addr) = self.listener.accept().await.unwrap();  // 💥
```
When FDs are exhausted, `accept()` returns `Err`, and `unwrap()` panics.

### 3. Resource Tracking is Broken
The `active_connections` Vec serves no purpose since:
- It stores `std::net::TcpStream` (blocking)
- But the actual connection uses `tokio::net::TcpStream` (async)
- The stored stream is never used

## Fix #1: Proper Error Handling

```rust
impl ConnectionHandler {
    pub async fn accept(&mut self) -> std::io::Result<()> {
        loop {
            match self.listener.accept().await {
                Ok((socket, addr)) => {
                    tracing::info!("New connection from: {}", addr);
                    tokio::spawn(handle_connection(socket));
                }
                Err(e) if e.kind() == std::io::ErrorKind::WouldBlock => {
                    // Transient, retry
                    tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(10)).await;
                }
                Err(e) => {
                    tracing::error!("Accept error: {:?}", e);
                    // Back off on FD exhaustion
                    if e.raw_os_error() == Some(24) {  // EMFILE
                        tracing::warn!("FD exhaustion - backing off");
                        tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1)).await;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## Fix #2: Connection Tracking with Cleanup

If you need to track active connections (for graceful shutdown, etc.):

```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};
use std::sync::Arc;

pub struct ConnectionHandler {
    listener: TcpListener,
    active_count: Arc<AtomicUsize>,
    max_connections: usize,
}

impl ConnectionHandler {
    pub async fn accept(&self) -> std::io::Result<()> {
        loop {
            // Back-pressure: reject if at capacity
            let current = self.active_count.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
            if current >= self.max_connections {
                tracing::warn!("At connection limit ({})", self.max_connections);
                tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(100)).await;
                continue;
            }

            match self.listener.accept().await {
                Ok((socket, addr)) => {
                    let counter = self.active_count.clone();
                    counter.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);

                    tokio::spawn(async move {
                        handle_connection(socket).await;
                        counter.fetch_sub(1, Ordering::Relaxed);  // Decrement on close!
                    });
                }
                Err(e) => {
                    tracing::error!("Accept failed: {:?}", e);
                    tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(50)).await;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

